Finally, teachers will be contacting all parents or students in the next two weeks to see what needs they have. Please remember to be patient with one another. Superintendent Gary Benda

post_text: See below for Mrs. Milder's first Art Challenge. If you haven't liked her page, Columbus Community Art K-12, please make sure you do!
shared_text:
Columbus Community Art K-12
April 13 at 2:30 PM ·

Your first challenge is today! Find an object or piece of food that you have in your house. Set it on a piece of paper and using any writing utensil, create an unique drawing! If you had fun, tried a few different ones! If you have siblings or family members around, challenge them to see who can come up with the most unique drawing! Maybe even use the same item and see the different things you all can come up with! Have fun and put your creations in the comments for all to see!

It's a new week! Happy Monday!

From this point on, please find daily activities on the CCSD Continuous Learning Opportunities document located on the district's home page: www.columbuscsd.org

Check out the resources the teachers have provided for you in order to stay engaged in your learning during this school closure. Also, please check in with the teachers during their scheduled Office Hours (located on the document).

As a reminder, these resources and activities are voluntary, but we encourage you to use them!

Enjoy this GOOD FRIDAY with your family (those in your house, of course)! Have a wonderful weekend! Maybe you want to try a few of these ideas below! #RoundyProud

🥚Dye some eggs.

🥚Hide eggs in your yard (or any other objects) and go on a hunt!

📝Create a word search with a list of spring or Easter words and ask someone to find your words.

🐰Go outside and do some bunny hops!

🐰Create a Pin the Tail on the Bunny game!

🌈Decorate your sidewalks or driveway with eggs using sidewalk chalk.

Happy Monday! Here are some ideas to keep busy as you start the week! #RoundyProud

🔖Design a bookmark for a book you are reading. Include words and pictures for details.

📝Interview a family member about their favorites (food, color, snack, animal, number, activity, etc.).

🧮Make your own math flashcards. Write the answers on the back. Practice your facts alone or with someone else.

📚Read a book or chapter while lying on your back!

💻Check out The Wiggle Tales on www.youtube.com for some great social/emotional learning.

post_text: Today's Columbus School Staff Parade was nothing short of AMAZING! Staff members separately drove in 51 cars and paraded through Columbus City, Columbus Junction, Fredonia, and Conesville to honk, wave, smile, and shout, "WE MISS YOU!" to our students and their families, as well as many other community members! You won't be able to scroll too far on Facebook without seeing pictures and videos of this heartfelt event. We want to thank the CJ Police and Conesville Police for escorting the staff through the streets. Most of all, we want to thank our students and families for brightening our day by allowing us to see the excitement on your faces! We truly miss all of you! We are #W4L!

Under state and federal law, Iowa is required to publish report cards reflecting every public school’s performance on multiple measures. These Iowa School Performance Profiles help stakeholders understand how their schools are serving students, as well as identify those schools that require support and improvements provided by the state. Report cards and designations were released to the public today.

This year, the Columbus Community School District is PROUD to CELEBRATE their performance in all three schools:

*Roundy Elementary moved up from the Acceptable category last year to COMMENDABLE.
*Columbus Junior High received a designation of ACCEPTABLE.
*Columbus High School received a designation of COMMENDABLE.

NO schools in our district require targeted support or improvement at the state level. This is GREAT NEWS!! CONGRATULATIONS to the students, staff, and community!

To view the data and information provided in the Iowa School Performance Profiles, please use the link found on the CCSD webpage. www.columbuscsd.org

post_text:
The Columbus Middle School (7th and 8th grade students) spent the past 3.5 weeks collecting spare change for their Change for Change project. They had a goal to raise $1000. They ended with a whopping $1800 raised! This is one of the highest amounts of money this project has raised in the 21 years the school has been doing it. If you see a middle school student, thank them for their hard work and generosity this holiday season.

The students got to spend a day buying presents for 21 different children in our school district with the money they raised. Local church members also contributed by buying presents for 9 other students and, in addition, with some of the extra money, we sponsored 4 Angel Tree children as well. Lastly, we donated money to a family that had their house damaged by a house fire. This brings our total to 35 different children helped in the Columbus School District this holiday season.

Thank you to any and all parents, family members, staff, and students who donated to this wonderful project! It wouldn't have been possible without all the support.
text:
The Columbus Middle School (7th and 8th grade students) spent the past 3.5 weeks collecting spare change for their Change for Change project. They had a goal to raise $1000. They ended with a whopping $1800 raised! This is one of the highest amounts of money this project has raised in the 21 years the school has been doing it. If you see a middle school student, thank them for their hard work and generosity this holiday season.

The students got to spend a day buying presents for 21 different children in our school district with the money they raised. Local church members also contributed by buying presents for 9 other students and, in addition, with some of the extra money, we sponsored 4 Angel Tree children as well. Lastly, we donated money to a family that had their house damaged by a house fire. This brings our total to 35 different children helped in the Columbus School District this holiday season.

Thank you to any and all parents, family members, staff, and students who donated to this wonderful project! It wouldn't have been possible without all the support.

post_text:
We have finished 20 school days and we want to thank all parents, community members, students and staff for making those days very successful. Prior to the school year we pushed out a lot of information about the Secondary Building Personal Technology Devices (PTDs) expectations. Their usage is down and we are seeing a gain in less student anxiety to check their phones and more class time devoted towards learning. However, we still see many students bringing them to class. Remember that if PTDs are brought to class, they should be turned into the teacher prior to the start of class and will be returned when class is over.

The four times during the school day students can access PTDs are: Before and After School, Passing Periods and Lunch. The four places that you can secure your PTDs are: Teacher's room, Locker, Office and Home.

Thank you for a great start to our school year and please remember our PTD expectations!!! Go Cats!

post_text:
At Monday night's board meeting, the board decided to make up the student hours and teacher days in the following manner:

April 10 was No School/Professional Development Day. That is now a regular school day with students.

All Wednesdays beginning March 20 through the end of the year will become regular dismissal days.

May 28 and 29 will be regular school days with students.

This makes up all of our student hours. Any additional hours missed will add May 30 as a student day.

Add 30 minutes to the teacher day beginning March 18. This makes up 4 days.

June 3, 4 and 5 will be professional development days for staff.

This makes up all of the teacher days.

post_text: All Activities are cancelled January 24th. We are proceeding with school and will try to get through the full day. We knew we could get children to and from school today safely. However, the the wind is going to drop the temperature very quickly late this afternoon and early this evening. The temperatures will be in the very negative degree mark for the next few days. Make sure your students are dressing for the cold weather. Not only to be outside, but also for riding in school buses. It takes school buses 30 minutes to warm up and they can be very cold until they are warm. As we watch the temperatures drop and the wind pick up, we will be watching the weather and roads to decide about delays and cancellations. Please be safe during these inclement weather time.

post_text:
Columbus CSD Families,

In mid-December, the state of Iowa published their new Iowa School Performance Review now that we operate under new federal regulations known as ESSA or the Every Student Succeeds Act. The score takes student academic achievement, proficiency, growth and view of the school into consideration.

Roundy Elementary, Columbus Junior High and High School all scored very well! Because of our score, we do not qualify for any of the designated lists requiring additional support or review from the state. Attached is a letter that includes more information about how scores and figured and what they mean.

This is a reason to celebrate! The students, teachers, staff, parents, and community have all worked very hard the past few years and our efforts are beginning to pay off! The staff is also dedicated to continuing moving the district forward in a positive direction.

Have a great weekend everybody!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I5CUvVGkdQA&list=UUNsSflRHpBdY2nC0Jv0mxZA
